Kh&aacute;nh, ph&iacute;a Đ&ocirc;ng gi&aacute;p Biển Đ&ocirc;ng.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img src="http://phuocnh/tomatocms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cba2c0dd5e_crop.jpg" alt="" /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Đường ven biển</em></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em><br /></em></p>\r\n<h2>Đồng bằng Di&ecirc;n Kh&aacute;nh - Nha Trang</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><br />Nha Trang nằm ở ph&iacute;a Đ&ocirc;ng Đồng bằng Di&ecirc;n Kh&aacute;nh - Nha Trang. Một đồng bằng được bồi lấp bởi s&ocirc;ng C&aacute;i Nha Trang c&oacute; diện t&iacute;ch gần 300 km&sup2;, địa h&igrave;nh đ&ograve;ng bằng bị ph&acirc;n h&oacute;a mạnh:<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * phần ph&iacute;a T&acirc;y dọc s&ocirc;ng Ch&ograve; từ Kh&aacute;nh B&igrave;nh đến Di&ecirc;n Đồng bị b&oacute;c m&ograve;n, độ cao tuyệt đối khoảng 10-20 m<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * phần ph&iacute;a Đ&ocirc;ng l&agrave; địa h&igrave;nh t&iacute;ch tụ độ cao tuyệt đối dưới 10m, bề mặt địa h&igrave;nh bị ph&acirc;n cắt mạnh bởi c&aacute;c d&ograve;ng chảy.</p>', 'Wikipedia', '', '15:44:04', 1, 'admin');
INSERT INTO news_article_revision (revision_id, article_id, category_id, title, sub_title, slug, description, content, author, icons, created_date, created_user_id, created_user_name) VALUES (75, 23, 2, 'Colled cake', '', 'colled-cake', '<p style="text-align: justify;">B&aacute;nh cuốn (literally "rolled cake") is a dish from northern Vietnam.</p>', '<p style="text-align: justify;">It is a cr&ecirc;pe-like roll made from a thin, wide sheet of rice flour filled with ground pork, minced wood ear mushroom, and other ingredients. Sides for this dish usually consist of chả lụa (Vietnamese pork sausage) and bean sprouts, with the dipping sauce called nước chấm. Sometimes, a drop of c&agrave; cuống, which is the essence of a giant water bug, Lethocerus indicus, is added to the nước chấm for extra flavor, although this ingredient is scarce and quite expensive.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><img src="http://phuocnh/tomatocms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc37ba9053_small.jpg" alt="" /> <img src="http://phuocnh/tomatocms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc37d048e1_small.JPG" alt="" /> <img src="http://phuocnh/tomatocms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc37e5c955_small.jpg" alt="" /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Unlike shahe fen, the rice sheet in b&aacute;nh cuốn is extremely thin and delicate. It is a light dish, and is generally eaten for breakfast everywhere in Vietnam. A different version of b&aacute;nh cuốn, called b&aacute;nh cuốn Thanh Tr&igrave; and b&aacute;nh cuốn l&agrave;ng K&ecirc;nh, may be found in Thanh Tr&igrave;, a southern district of Hanoi and K&ecirc;nh village of Nam Định, an ancient village in the centre of Nam Định city.B&aacute;nh cuốn Thanh Tr&igrave; or B&aacute;nh cuốn l&agrave;ng K&ecirc;nh are not rolls, but just rice sheets eaten with chả lụa, fried shallots, or prawns; see the article B&aacute;nh cuốn in the Vietnamese Wikipedia.<br /><br />A similar Chinese dish is the Cantonese dish coeng4 fan2 (肠粉; pinyin: ch&aacute;ngfěn), usually translated into English as "steamed rice roll" or "rice noodle roll," which is a form of dim sum.</p>', 'Wikipedia', '', '15:59:15', 1, 'admin');
